(c) On or before December 31 of each year, the board shall submit a report to
the chief clerk of each house of the general assembly containing aggregated, de-
identified data on the following:
(1) Statistics on the number and percentage of nurse practitioners who
responded to the survey;
(2) The percentage of nurse practitioners who reported having a
collaborating physician in the same specialty;
(3) The percentage of collaborating physicians who are on-site with
nurse practitioners full time, and for those not on-site full time, the average
number of days per week the collaborating physician is on-site; and
(4) Such other statistics that the board may deem to be useful in
informing the general assembly on the collaborating relationship between
physicians and nurse practitioners who practice a specialty.
(d) The board shall include in the report required by subsection (c) any data
collected on or before December 1 of each year.
(e) The board may publish and deliver the report required by subsection (c) by
electronic means.
(f) As used in this section, "specialty" means:
(1) As the term relates to a nurse practitioner, an area of the study of
nursing completed by a nurse practitioner that leads to a national specialty
certification by an organization recognized by the board of nursing; and
(2) As the term relates to a physician, an area of the study of medicine
completed by a physician that leads to board certification by a board approved by
the American Board of Medical Specialties.
SECTION 2. This act takes effect upon becoming a law, the public welfare requiring it.
